import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="Get started" current="docs">
  <h1>Get started</h1>
  <p style="font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--fg-soft); max-width: 70ch;">
    Prime is a CLI for compiling, querying, and installing knowledge atoms.
    Five minutes from zero to first atom.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Install the CLI</h2>
  <pre><code># Bun (fastest)
bun add -g @prime/cli

# Or npm
npm i -g @prime/cli</code></pre>

  <h2>2. Install a corpus</h2>
  <p>
    Corpora are folders of atoms. Install one from a remote registry:
  </p>
  <pre><code>prime install @recipes
# → ./prime/sources/@recipes/...</code></pre>

  <p>
    Or compile a local one:
  </p>
  <pre><code>cd my-corpus
prime compile
# → ./primes/compiled/_index.xml + per-atom folders</code></pre>

  <h2>3. Inspect atoms</h2>
  <pre><code># List atoms in the local corpus
prime list

# Show one atom — metadata, all edges, graph fan-out
prime show @recipes/method-pan-sauce

# Walk the dependency tree
prime deps @recipes/method-pan-sauce</code></pre>

  <h2>4. Query from an agent (MCP)</h2>
  <p>
    The MCP server exposes <code>prime_query</code> / <code>prime_resolve</code> /
    <code>prime_intent</code> / <code>prime_validate</code> / <code>prime_compile</code>
    tools to any MCP-capable client (Claude Code, Cursor, Continue, …).
  </p>
  <pre><code># Boot the server on the compiled corpus
PRIME_DIR=primes/compiled bunx @prime-lang/mcp-server-core</code></pre>

  <h2>5. Publish</h2>
  <p>
    When your corpus is ready, publish it for others to install:
  </p>
  <pre><code>prime publish --remote https://your-registry.example</code></pre>

  <h2>What is an atom?</h2>
  <p>
    An atom is a self-contained typed unit of knowledge. It has:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A <strong>kind</strong> — fact, rule, pattern, anti-pattern, method, term, principle, tradeoff, or collection.</li>
    <li>A <strong>domain</strong> — a tag declaring which subject area it lives in (cooking, coding-style, …).</li>
    <li>Three <strong>projection levels</strong>: <code>summary</code> (~30 tokens), <code>core</code> (~150 tokens), <code>full</code> (~380 tokens). Pick the smallest one that fits your context window.</li>
    <li><strong>Edges</strong> to other atoms with explicit verbs: <code>requires</code>, <code>supplies-to</code>, <code>related</code>, <code>see-also</code>, <code>enhances</code>, <code>includes</code>, …</li>
  </ul>

